5|$|Agagianian was {{elevated}} to the cardinalate in 1946 by Pope Pius XII. He was Prefect of the Congregation for the Propagation of the Faith (Propaganda Fide) from 1958 to 1970. A theological liberal, linguist, and <b>an</b> <b>authority</b> <b>on</b> the Soviet Union, {{he served as}} one of the four moderators at the Second Vatican Council and was twice considered a serious papal candidate, during the conclaves of 1958 and 1963.|$|E
5|$|Balch was {{a member}} of caving clubs such as the Wessex Cave Club. He was a serious speleologist and often made ten-hour trips wearing cloth cap, old suit and tie. Balch Cave near Stoke St Michael is named after him. As <b>an</b> <b>authority</b> <b>on</b> the caves under the Mendip Hills, Balch was {{consulted}} by water companies who were looking for new water supplies.|$|E
5|$|Balch {{was awarded}} an honorary Master of Arts by Bristol University in July 1927 for devoting his leisure time to {{exploring}} and recording the caves of the Mendip Hills, becoming <b>an</b> <b>authority</b> <b>on</b> the subject. He retired as postmaster on 31 March 1931, whilst continuing his caving, working as the {{curator at the}} museum and giving lectures on archaeology.|$|E
